               <msContents>
                  <summary>Mahzor according to the Western Ashkenazi rite for the whole
                     year</summary>
                  <msItem>
                     <title type="desc" xml:lang="he" key="work_221">מחזור מנהג אשכנז המערבי לכל
                        השנה</title>
                     <title type="desc" xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc" key="work_221">Maḥzor minhag
                        Ashkenaz ha-maʻaravi le-khol ha-shanah</title>
                     <textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
                     <note>Used for variants in Daniel Goldschmidt's edition of the High Holiday
                        services (Jerusalem, 1970).</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>parchment</support>
                        <extent>ff. 400 <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>432</height>
                              <width>300</width>
                           </dimensions></extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary>Ashkenazic square script</summary>
                     <handNote>Copied by <persName>Shlomoh ben Shimʿon ha-Sofer he-Ḥazan</persName> <foreign
                           xml:lang="he">שלמה בן שמעון הסופר החזן</foreign> (colophon on <locus>f.
                           396v</locus>); <locus>ff. 375v-381v and 397r-400v</locus> are by another
                        hand.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>A few initial words are decorated with penwork; some of these,
                        including <locus>ff. 19r, 99v, 252v, 312v,</locus> are coloured with a light
                        yellow wash. The catchwords are embellished with monochrome penwork animal,
                        vegetal or abstract motifs. On <locus>f. 375v</locus>, within the portion of
                        the manuscript that has been copied by a different scribe, the initial word
                           <foreign xml:lang="he">אאמיץ</foreign> is decorated with much more
                        intricate penwork and coloured with light washes in red and
                        green.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <p>Light brown leather over thick paper boards. </p>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate>[late 13th cent.]</origDate>
                     <origPlace>[Germany]</origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>On both sides of <locus>f. 1</locus>, numerous ownership inscriptions
                     including those of Anshel ben Yiśraʾel Yosef Yitsḥaḳ from <placeName
                        key="place_92">Eggingen</placeName>
                     <foreign xml:lang="he">אנשיל בן ישראל יוסף יצחק דעקינגן</foreign>, and of
                     Eliezer ben Asher Oppenheim <foreign xml:lang="he">אליעזר בן אשר
                        אופנהיים</foreign> and his sons, Yehudah, Shlomoh, Simeon and Asher ben
                     Eliezer Oppenheim and possibly also a grandson who was also called Eliezer ben
                     Asher Oppenheim.</provenance>
                  <acquisition>It belonged to <persName ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/7753200"
                        key="person_7753200">David ben Abraham Oppenheim</persName>'s <date
                        calendar="#Gregorian">(1664-1736)</date> library, which was purchased by the
                     Bodleian Library in <date calendar="#Gregorian">1829</date>.</acquisition>
               </history>
